<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-23T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-23T04:00:00-05:00" n="98" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d98">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2625</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-23T17:00:00+08:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 23, 1917, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Reports from various parts of China indicate that the American note has
                            been effective in putting emphatically before the several parties and
                            sections the necessity of national unity, predisposing them to make a
                            compromise.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>